OTnyk6vZRkutrOJQmNALkN5Cz0eXmiaoA0Ej13j-4OULGfXbeH2D68-3zz-PFJk1svQ77HYthHfFljii92uD6eEeIJ5SaNQmth0_A6LLhLY42lXq2-bYpUM1mGHLzH6ifqo_C__fqmufEAOEzBORGtNXdh4uC0TD-QZTOv4Zr4haBlm_9ZAGT9YzMMTJngOssQ==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering JAR resources**\\n\\nI'm noticing that the `META-INF/MANIFEST.MF` resources are duplicating with what gets generated. I wonder if Gradle's JAR can merge them? I recall that the default behavior for Copy's duplicatesStrategy is INHERIT, but the root is set to EXCLUDE. It's an interesting situation, and I might need to check the configuration to see how merging works and if tweaking it would help resolve this duplication issue.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dynamic loading issues**\\n\\nI'm diving into the potential issues with duplicate MANIFEST.MF resources in native plugin builds. It seems that the test executable might be using class directories instead of the test jar. Could I create a temporary jar on the classpath at runtime using URLClassLoader? Maybe the active call target from URLClassLoader#getResources isn't working as expected. I should also explore if generating a temp jar for tests containing META-INF/MANIFEST.MF could help, though it raises questions about native image support for dynamic resources post-build.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating URLClassLoader limitations**\\n\\nI'm questioning whether URLClassLoader will function properly in a native environment. It looks like resources from jars created at runtime won't be included in the Native Image, which could lead to a failure during execution—a situation we definitely want to avoid. Using the standard `src/test/resources/META-INF/MANIFEST.MF` might be fine, but I wonder if source resources are included by default. I'll need to assert that the \\\"akka-manifest-info-test\\\" isn't affected by classloader behavior, and maybe add a second test with the public API to ensure coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing resource coverage**\\n\\nI'm pondering whether coverage of resource metadata will work if it's outside the active class; it might not register the call site directly. However, if the coverage is based on generated metadata, it could record resource access correctly. But what if the active class contains test resources? If I ensure the agent can see resources with the standard classloader, maybe that counts as coverage. Still, I'm considering using the ManifestInfo extension during ActorSystem startup to see if we can address any gaps regarding versions lacking test resources.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating dynamic coverage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how dynamic coverage detects the call site through the stack frame when the agent intercepts getResources. It seems to work with the standard AppClassLoader but not with custom class loaders since they aren't instrumented by the native agent. This might mean I need to fix that. I also wonder if I should remove certain imports, like Version, and consider if there's a user-code filter that allows for testing resources. There's a lot to sift through here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Updated the `ManifestInfo` coverage test to use a real classpath manifest resource instead of a custom/temp resource loader.\n\nChanges:\n\n- Rewrote `ManifestInfoTest.scala` to:\n  - Use the default `ActorSystem` classloader.\n  - Instantiate `akka.util.ManifestInfo` directly from the `ExtendedActorSystem`.\n  - Assert that a known-vendor manifest is discovered.\n  - Exercise `checkSameVersion` for the discovered manifest entry.\n\n- Added a test classpath manifest resource:\n  - `tests/src/com.typesafe.akka/akka-actor_2.13/2.8.8/src/test/resources/META-INF/MANIFEST.MF`\n\nThis should cause `ManifestInfo` to execute the remaining call site:\n\n```scala\nsystem.dynamicAccess.classLoader.getResources(\"META-INF/MANIFEST.MF\")\n```\n\nusing the normal classpath resource lookup path, which is more likely to be recognized by the dynamic-access coverage tooling than the previous custom `ClassLoader` override.\n\nPer instructions, I did not run tests locally.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0c2f72ae2b6870480169fb2d6b509881968c1262e7b0c44ea5\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 904, "output": 1345, "cacheRead": 40448, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42697, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1778068819260, "responseId": "resp_0c2f72ae2b6870480169fb2d53d1788196ba202aa329d58757"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering JAR resources**\n\nI'm noticing that the `META-INF/MANIFEST.MF` resources are duplicating with what gets generated. I wonder if Gradle's JAR can merge them? I recall that the default behavior for Copy's duplicatesStrategy is INHERIT, but the root is set to EXCLUDE. It's an interesting situation, and I might need to check the configuration to see how merging works and if tweaking it would help resolve this duplication issue.\n\n**Considering dynamic loading issues**\n\nI'm diving into the potential issues with duplicate MANIFEST.MF resources in native plugin builds. It seems that the test executable might be using class directories instead of the test jar. Could I create a temporary jar on the classpath at runtime using URLClassLoader? Maybe the active call target from URLClassLoader#getResources isn't working as expected. I should also explore if generating a temp jar for tests containing META-INF/MANIFEST.MF could help, though it raises questions about native image support for dynamic resources post-build.\n\n**Evaluating URLClassLoader limitations**\n\nI'm questioning whether URLClassLoader will function properly in a native environment. It looks like resources from jars created at runtime won't be included in the Native Image, which could lead to a failure during execution—a situation we definitely want to avoid. Using the standard `src/test/resources/META-INF/MANIFEST.MF` might be fine, but I wonder if source resources are included by default. I'll need to assert that the \"akka-manifest-info-test\" isn't affected by classloader behavior, and maybe add a second test with the public API to ensure coverage.\n\n**Assessing resource coverage**\n\nI'm pondering whether coverage of resource metadata will work if it's outside the active class; it might not register the call site directly. However, if the coverage is based on generated metadata, it could record resource access correctly. But what if the active class contains test resources? If I ensure the agent can see resources with the standard classloader, maybe that counts as coverage. Still, I'm considering using the ManifestInfo extension during ActorSystem startup to see if we can address any gaps regarding versions lacking test resources.\n\n**Evaluating dynamic coverage**\n\nI'm thinking about how dynamic coverage detects the call site through the stack frame when the agent intercepts getResources. It seems to work with the standard AppClassLoader but not with custom class loaders since they aren't instrumented by the native agent. This might mean I need to fix that. I also wonder if I should remove certain imports, like Version, and consider if there's a user-code filter that allows for testing resources. There's a lot to sift through here!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c2f72ae2b6870480169fb2d55880881969d439f38e2749e83\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-y1rgmPcfTuOlpWjHvwWjMPanQWIramJXVxgNfIoeM1pjXSjSUsifnJeAK2IuO2j2ajGc7FeKSqzZ8pOJCoqBBPk0eAzeOt8B7VTG1e6yuRzjQKgjVkUQjOAjhPaBTXwQu5sOexbwchavf4ldaF9_8dLbflen8T3wXQfTnEpS_QTViCB6NhHQTuEtHxpK_Wzgh3cE2BOorGk2g42vykvlMZc7o82l0Tz55VcddgjHVV-8QnZLMIWE2QKxkVFjSbKkzt_sVhvpQJUNzPvKRvbnFZhwj4diiLZcUuZ8Fh86Bb88t3BtHN5H6Wk2DktaQQF5nw1XMTqW-2KpqClE7kdN1Lg2aDYVuPyCrz1QXGZP8fAucwi-haOR14fJ6MhbCw_nOHLPUdg7E58WQLnf7tyGKlYsScmaE_ocCVobWBERA__Ojh9cB8g3S7mOVUUgpGuYrVG5ff-IkyDQ2BXw_6MsjESmKudn1HQtA8kqE5sZ-SgPI5UNkPOBii301triNsHTkVcrSOKHTbYoF9b43FuIWX-_6FtI7Q6-w3Klnc6wzI6gieqrYYnok_MQEJ7u4nywBbtnd-rOIYm_Y2iHGM-uEkEO3yZErYS-KHnPSSdoivzL_LnTO4Xg8IZSzCcUFt6ny0CnoJGYJFcOsqj8gzPtsJtmQdhDg0jEiK9DM1-IfotclCiwOSqhGT9QSV85zCBEfwy-O5qro913QZ3nZ7Js_F0Cla7uhyNj5wb9F3YqS0ls3BVcHmUfTAVuj-_T1Kh6hGZ9kso1L99oIwav0XKp0YOv_F3VPC_FHaK7UF98z8-AKkD9DVLfq0XvFqAMQ9RoO0JtkjTyWS3QyUJVz_1bktVaKbXCWVYjmpTizIEm-tcot_KoBO5HPNfVMXdzehODOwdigrz2pNVwCKDGJErBNZcwuryRp5nmOK941_5cZ_4K_6w4V4WOQVrOnwz4DJj54tUvSo63sJz4lZFHhhkhRGsvI-